                    "question_id": 14720331,
                    "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/14720331/how-to-generate-random-colors-in-matplotlib/58746732#58746732",
                    "body": "<p>If you want to ensure the colours are distinct - but don't know how many colours are needed. Try something like this. It selects colours from opposite sides of the spectrum and systematically increases granularity. </p>\n\n<pre><code>import math\n\ndef calc(val, max = 16):\n    if val &lt; 1:\n        return 0\n    if val == 1:\n        return max\n\n    l = math.floor(math.log2(val-1))    #level \n    d = max/2**(l+1)                    #devision\n    n = val-2**l                        #node\n    return d*(2*n-1)\n</code></pre>\n\n<pre><code>import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\nN = 16\ncmap = cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap('gist_rainbow', N)\n\nfig, axs = plt.subplots(2)\nfor ax in axs:\n    ax.set_xlim([ 0, N])\n    ax.set_ylim([-0.5, 0.5])\n    ax.set_yticks([])\n\nfor i in range(0,N+1):\n    v = int(calc(i, max = N))\n    rect0 = plt.Rectangle((i, -0.5), 1, 1, facecolor=cmap(i))\n    rect1 = plt.Rectangle((i, -0.5), 1, 1, facecolor=cmap(v))\n    axs[0].add_artist(rect0)\n    axs[1].add_artist(rect1)\n\nplt.xticks(range(0, N), [int(calc(i, N)) for i in range(0, N)])\nplt.show()\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Y5ff5.png\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">output</a></p>\n\n<p>Thanks to @Ali for providing the base implementation.</p>\n"
